# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electrical-reactance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electrical-reactance/addison-wesley] The Addison–Wesley Professional Imprint produces content including books, eBooks, and video for the professional IT worker including developers, programmers, managers, system administrators.
[src:electrical-reactance/addison-wesley] Classic titles include *The Art of Computer Programming*, *The C++ Programming Language*, *The Mythical Man-Month*, and *Design Patterns*.
[src:electrical-reactance/addison-wesley] Lew Addison Cummings and Melbourne Wesley Cummings founded Addison–Wesley in 1942, with the first book published by Addison–Wesley being Massachusetts Institute of Technology professor Francis Weston Sears' *Mechanics*.
[src:electrical-reactance/addison-wesley] Its first computer book was *Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, by Wilkes, Wheeler, and Gill.
[src:electrical-reactance/addison-wesley] Benjamin Company, and merged it with the Cummings division of the company to form Benjamin Cummings.
[src:electrical-reactance/addison-wesley] It was purchased by the global publishing and education company Pearson PLC in 1988 and became part of Addison Wesley Longman in 1994.
[src:electrical-reactance/addison-wesley] The trade publishing division of Addison–Wesley was sold to Perseus Books Group in 1997, leaving Addison–Wesley as solely an educational publisher.
[src:electrical-reactance/addison-wesley] Pearson acquired the educational division of Simon & Schuster in 1998, and merged it with Addison Wesley Longman to form Pearson Education and subsequently rebranded to Pearson in 2011.
[src:electrical-reactance/addison-wesley] Pearson moved the former Addison Wesley Longman offices from Reading, Massachusetts, to Boston in 2004.
[src:electrical-reactance/addison-wesley] Its current executives hail from the original Addison–Wesley with a storied history of their own.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:electrical-reactance/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The **American Institute of Electrical Engineers** (**AIEE**) was a United States–based organization of electrical engineers that existed from 1884 through 1962.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] On January 1, 1963, it merged with the Institute of Radio Engineers (IRE) to form the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE).
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The 1884 founders of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers (AIEE) included some of the most prominent inventors and innovators in the then new field of electrical engineering, among them Nikola Tesla, Thomas Alva Edison, Elihu Thomson, Edwin J.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Other notable AIEE presidents were Alexander Graham Bell (1891–1892), Charles Proteus Steinmetz (1901–1902), Bion J.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The first technical meeting of the AIEE was held during the International Electrical Exhibition of 1884 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on October 7–8, at the Franklin Institute.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] After several years of operating primarily in New York City, the AIEE authorized local sections in 1902.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] These were first formed in the United States in Chicago and Ithaca, New York, in 1902, and then in other countries.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The first section outside the United States, established in 1903, was in Toronto, Canada.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] AIEE's regional structure was soon complemented by a technical structure.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The first technical committee of AIEE, the High Voltage Transmission Committee, was formed in 1903.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Standardization work started in 1891 with the formation of a committee on units and standards, followed by a committee on standard wiring.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] At the 50th anniversary of the organization, there were 10 women members, including Edith Clarke (associate member in 1923, member in 1933) and Mabel MacFerran Rockwell (associate member in 1928, member in 1935).
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The formation of the AIEE Subcommittee on Large-Scale Computing in 1946 was considered a key milestone in the history of computer engineering, representing the first time that a professional association recognized the significance of computers and computing in electro-technology.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The early technical areas of interest of AIEE were electric power, lighting, and wired communications.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Radio and wireless communications became the major focus of a rival organization, the Institute of Radio Engineers (the IRE, established 1912).
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The dynamic growth of radio technology and the emergence of the new discipline of electronics in the 1940s led to stiff competition between AIEE and IRE, with IRE showing faster growth in the 1950s and early 1960s, and attracting more students.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] In 1957, the IRE, with approximately 55,500 members, surpassed the AIEE in membership size; by 1962 the IRE had 96,500 members to the AIEE's 57,000.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Although the AIEE was a member-volunteer run organization, it relied on a paid staff for daily operations.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The photos that accompanied the article not only included images of the women who worked there, but unusual for the time, also named them.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Female employees of the AIEE included Miss Mary E.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] After the AIEE's founding in 1884, its member's badge was created in 1893 by a committee headed by Alexander Graham Bell, AIEE's president from 1891 to 1892.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The badge's logo depicted Benjamin Franklin's kite, representative of the discovery that lightning carried electricity.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The design also showed a winding of gold wire with its midpoints crossed by a galvanometer's indicator, invoking the electrical engineer's Wheatstone bridge.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Ohm's law and the letters "AIEE" were added in gold at the logo's base.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The busy logo design was replaced four years later.
[src:electrical-reactance/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The AIEE and the IRE merged in 1963 to form the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), in short order becoming the world's largest technical society.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] The **amplitude** of a periodic variable is a measure of its change in a single period (such as time or spatial period).
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] The amplitude of a non-periodic signal is its magnitude compared with a reference value.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] There are various definitions of amplitude (see below), which are all functions of the magnitude of the differences between the variable's extreme values.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] In older texts, the phase of a periodic function is sometimes called the amplitude.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] In audio system measurements, telecommunications and others where the measurand is a signal that swings above and below a reference value but is not sinusoidal, peak amplitude is often used.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] If the reference is zero, this is the maximum absolute value of the signal; if the reference is a mean value (DC component), the peak amplitude is the maximum absolute value of the difference from that reference.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Semi-amplitude means half of the peak-to-peak amplitude.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] The majority of scientific literature employs the term *amplitude* or *peak amplitude* to mean semi-amplitude.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] It is the most widely used measure of orbital wobble in astronomy and the measurement of small radial velocity semi-amplitudes of nearby stars is important in the search for exoplanets (see Doppler spectroscopy).
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Root mean square (RMS) amplitude is used especially in electrical engineering: the RMS is defined as the square root of the mean over time of the square of the vertical distance of the graph from the rest state; i.e. the RMS of the AC waveform (with no DC component).
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] For complicated waveforms, especially non-repeating signals like noise, the RMS amplitude is usually used because it is both unambiguous and has physical significance.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] For example, the *average* power transmitted by an acoustic or electromagnetic wave or by an electrical signal is proportional to the square of the RMS amplitude (and not, in general, to the square of the peak amplitude).
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] For alternating current electric power, the universal practice is to specify RMS values of a sinusoidal waveform.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] One property of root mean square voltages and currents is that they produce the same heating effect as a direct current in a given resistance.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] The peak-to-peak value is used, for example, when choosing rectifiers for power supplies, or when estimating the maximum voltage that insulation must withstand.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Some common voltmeters are calibrated for RMS amplitude, but respond to the average value of a rectified waveform.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Many digital voltmeters and all moving coil meters are in this category.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] The RMS calibration is only correct for a sine wave input since the ratio between peak, average and RMS values is dependent on waveform.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] If the wave shape being measured is greatly different from a sine wave, the relationship between RMS and average value changes.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] True RMS-responding meters were used in radio frequency measurements, where instruments measured the heating effect in a resistor to measure a current.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] The advent of microprocessor-controlled meters capable of calculating RMS by sampling the waveform has made true RMS measurement commonplace.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] In telecommunications, *pulse amplitude* is the magnitude of a pulse parameter, such as the voltage level, current level, field intensity, or power level.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Pulse amplitude is measured with respect to a specified reference and therefore should be modified by qualifiers, such as *average*, *instantaneous*, *peak*, or *root-mean-square*.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Pulse amplitude also applies to the amplitude of frequency- and phase-modulated waveform envelopes.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] For symmetric periodic waves, like sine waves, square waves, or triangle waves, *peak amplitude* and *semi amplitude* are the same.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] However, for an asymmetric wave or wave packet (periodic pulses in one direction, for example), the peak amplitude becomes ambiguous.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] In electrical engineering, the usual solution to this ambiguity is to measure the amplitude from a defined reference potential (such as ground or 0 V).
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Strictly speaking, this is no longer amplitude since there is the possibility that a constant (DC component) is included in the measurement.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] The units of the amplitude depend on the type of wave, but are always in the same units as the oscillating variable.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] A more general representation of the wave equation is more complex, but the role of amplitude remains analogous to this simple case.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] For waves on a string, or in a medium such as water, the amplitude is a displacement.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] The amplitude of sound waves and audio signals (which relates to the volume) conventionally refers to the amplitude of the air pressure in the wave, but sometimes the amplitude of the displacement (movements of the air or the diaphragm of a speaker) is described.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] The logarithm of the amplitude squared is usually quoted in dB, so a null amplitude corresponds to −∞ dB.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Loudness is related to amplitude and intensity and is one of the most salient qualities of a sound, although in general sounds it can be recognized independently of amplitude.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] The square of the amplitude is proportional to the intensity of the wave.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] For electromagnetic radiation, the amplitude of a photon corresponds to the changes in the electric field of the wave.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] However, radio signals may be carried by electromagnetic radiation; the intensity of the radiation (amplitude modulation) or the frequency of the radiation (frequency modulation) is oscillated and then the individual oscillations are varied (modulated) to produce the signal.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Amplitude envelope refers to the changes in the amplitude of a sound over time, and is an influential property as it affects perception of timbre.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] A flat tone has a steady state amplitude that remains constant during time, which is represented by a scalar.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Other sounds can have percussive amplitude envelopes featuring an abrupt onset followed by an immediate exponential decay.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Percussive amplitude envelopes are characteristic of various impact sounds: two wine glasses clinking together, hitting a drum, slamming a door, etc. where the amplitude is transient and must be represented as either a continuous function or a discrete vector.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Percussive amplitude envelopes model many common sounds that have a transient loudness attack, decay, sustain, and release.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] With waveforms containing many overtones, complex transient timbres can be achieved by assigning each overtone to its own distinct transient amplitude envelope.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] Unfortunately, this has the effect of modulating the loudness of the sound as well.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] It makes more sense to separate loudness and harmonic quality to be parameters controlled independently of each other.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] To do so, harmonic amplitude envelopes are frame-by-frame normalized to become amplitude *proportion* envelopes, where at each time frame all the harmonic amplitudes will add to 100% (or 1).
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] This way, the main loudness-controlling envelope can be cleanly controlled.
[src:electrical-reactance/amplitude] In Sound Recognition, max amplitude normalization can be used to help align the key harmonic features of 2 alike sounds, allowing similar timbres to be recognized independent of loudness.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] Angular frequency (or angular speed) is the magnitude of the pseudovector quantity *angular velocity*.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] Angular frequency can be obtained by multiplying *rotational frequency*, *ν* (or ordinary *frequency*, *f*) by a full turn (2π radians): *ω* = 2π rad⋅*ν*.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] It can also be formulated as *ω* = d*θ*/d*t*, the instantaneous rate of change of the angular displacement, *θ*, with respect to time, *t*.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] In SI units, angular frequency is normally presented in the unit radian per second.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] The unit hertz (Hz) is dimensionally equivalent, but by convention it is only used for frequency *f*, never for angular frequency *ω*.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] This convention is used to help avoid the confusion that arises when dealing with quantities such as frequency and angular quantities because the units of measure (such as cycle or radian) are considered to be one and hence may be omitted when expressing quantities in terms of SI units.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] In digital signal processing, the frequency may be normalized by the sampling rate, yielding the normalized frequency.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] In a rotating or orbiting object, there is a relation between distance from the axis, r , tangential speed, v , and the angular frequency of the rotation.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] During one period, T , a body in circular motion travels a distance $vT$ .
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] This distance is also equal to the circumference of the path traced out by the body, $2\pi r$ .
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] An object attached to a spring can oscillate.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] As the object oscillates, its acceleration can be calculated by $a=-\omega ^{2}x,$ where *x* is displacement from an equilibrium position.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] Adding series resistance (for example, due to the resistance of the wire in a coil) does not change the resonant frequency of the series LC circuit.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] For a parallel tuned circuit, the above equation is often a useful approximation, but the resonant frequency does depend on the losses of parallel elements.
[src:electrical-reactance/angular-frequency] Although angular frequency is often loosely referred to as frequency, it differs from frequency by a factor of 2π, which potentially leads confusion when the distinction is not made clear.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The capacitance between two conductors depends on the opposing surface area of the conductors, the distance between those conductors, and the permittivity of any dielectric material between them.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] For many dielectric materials, the permittivity, and thus the capacitance, is independent of the potential difference between the conductors and the total charge on them.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The SI unit of capacitance is the farad (symbol: F), named after the English physicist Michael Faraday.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] A 1 farad capacitor, when charged with 1 coulomb of electrical charge, has a potential difference of 1 volt between its plates.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The reciprocal of capacitance is called elastance.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In discussing electrical circuits, the term *capacitance* is usually a shorthand for the mutual capacitance between two adjacent conductors, such as the two plates of a capacitor.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] However, every isolated conductor also exhibits capacitance, here called *self-capacitance*.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] It is measured by the amount of electric charge that must be added to an isolated conductor to raise its electric potential by one unit of measurement, e.g., one volt.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The reference point for this potential is a theoretical hollow conducting sphere, of infinite radius, with the conductor centered inside this sphere.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The inter-winding capacitance of a coil is sometimes called self-capacitance, but this is a different phenomenon.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] It is actually mutual capacitance between the individual turns of the coil and is a form of stray or parasitic capacitance.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] This self-capacitance is an important consideration at high frequencies: it changes the impedance of the coil and gives rise to parallel resonance.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In many applications this is an undesirable effect and sets an upper frequency limit for the correct operation of the circuit.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] A common form is a parallel-plate capacitor, which consists of two conductive plates insulated from each other, usually sandwiching a dielectric material.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In a parallel plate capacitor, capacitance is very nearly proportional to the surface area of the conductor plates and inversely proportional to the separation distance between the plates.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The discussion above is limited to the case of two conducting plates, although of arbitrary size and shape.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The definition $C=Q/V$ does not apply when there are more than two charged plates, or when the net charge on the two plates is non-zero.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] To handle this case, James Clerk Maxwell introduced his *coefficients of potential*.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] If three (nearly ideal) conductors are given charges $Q_{1},Q_{2},Q_{3}$ , then the voltage (actually potential) at conductor 1 is given by $V_{1}=P_{11}Q_{1}+P_{12}Q_{2}+P_{13}Q_{3},$ and similarly for the other voltages.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Hermann von Helmholtz and Sir William Thomson showed that the coefficients of potential are symmetric, so that $P_{12}=P_{21}$ , etc.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Similarly, the charge can be written in terms of voltages (actually potentials): $Q_{1}=C_{11}V_{1}+C_{12}V_{2}+C_{13}V_{3},$ The collection of coefficients $C_{ij}={\frac {\partial Q_{i}}{\partial V_{j}}}$ is known as the *capacitance matrix*,.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In open systems which are not charge neutral, so that field lines can end at infinity (which is implicitly assumed to have 0 potential in the above equations), the capacitance and elastance matrices are inverses of each other: $C^{-1}=P$ .
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In closed systems however the capacitance matrix is singular (it has a 0 eigenvalue due to charge neutrality), and so formally the elastance matrix as the inverse of the capacitance matrix is ill defined; it would require independently varying the charges.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Since no actual device holds perfectly equal and opposite charges on each of the two "plates", it is the mutual capacitance that is reported on capacitors.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The capacitance of the majority of capacitors used in electronic circuits is generally several orders of magnitude smaller than the farad.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The most common units of capacitance are the microfarad (μF), nanofarad (nF), picofarad (pF), and, in microcircuits, femtofarad (fF).
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Some applications also use supercapacitors that can be much larger, as much as hundreds of farads, and parasitic capacitive elements can be less than a femtofarad.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Historical texts use other, obsolete submultiples of the farad, such as "mf" and "mfd" for microfarad (μF); "mmf", "mmfd", "pfd", "μμF" for picofarad (pF).
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The capacitance can be calculated if the geometry of the conductors and the dielectric properties of the insulator between the conductors are known.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Capacitance is proportional to the area of overlap and inversely proportional to the separation between conducting sheets.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The closer the sheets are to each other, the greater the capacitance.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] An example is the capacitance of a capacitor constructed of two parallel plates both of area ${\textstyle A}$ separated by a distance ${\textstyle d}$ .
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The equation is a good approximation if *d* is small compared to the other dimensions of the plates so that the electric field in the capacitor area is uniform, and the so-called *fringing field* around the periphery provides only a small contribution to the capacitance.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Any two adjacent conductors can function as a capacitor, though the capacitance is small unless the conductors are close together for long distances or over a large area.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] This (often unwanted) capacitance is called parasitic or stray capacitance.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Stray capacitance can allow signals to leak between otherwise isolated circuits (an effect called crosstalk), and it can be a limiting factor for proper functioning of circuits at high frequency.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Stray capacitance between the input and output in amplifier circuits can be troublesome because it can form a path for feedback, which can cause instability and parasitic oscillation in the amplifier.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] It is often convenient for analytical purposes to replace this capacitance with a combination of one input-to-ground capacitance and one output-to-ground capacitance; the original configuration – including the input-to-output capacitance – is often referred to as a pi-configuration.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Since impedance varies inversely with capacitance, the internode capacitance, *C*, is replaced by a capacitance of KC from input to ground and a capacitance of ⁠(*K* − 1)*C*/*K*⁠ from output to ground.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] When the input-to-output gain is very large, the equivalent input-to-ground impedance is very small while the output-to-ground impedance is essentially equal to the original (input-to-output) impedance.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Calculating the capacitance of a system amounts to solving the Laplace equation ${\textstyle \nabla ^{2}\varphi =0}$ with a constant potential ${\textstyle \varphi }$ on the 2-dimensional surface of the conductors embedded in 3-space.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] There is no solution in terms of elementary functions in more complicated cases.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] For plane situations, analytic functions may be used to map different geometries to each other.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The energy (measured in joules) stored in a capacitor is equal to the *work* required to push the charges into the capacitor, i.e. to charge it.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Consider a capacitor of capacitance *C*, holding a charge +*q* on one plate and −*q* on the other.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The energy stored in a capacitor is found by integrating this equation.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The capacitance of nanoscale dielectric capacitors such as quantum dots may differ from conventional formulations of larger capacitors.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In particular, the electrostatic potential difference experienced by electrons in conventional capacitors is spatially well-defined and fixed by the shape and size of metallic electrodes in addition to the statistically large number of electrons present in conventional capacitors.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In nanoscale capacitors, however, the electrostatic potentials experienced by electrons are determined by the number and locations of all electrons that contribute to the electronic properties of the device.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In such devices, the number of electrons may be very small, so the resulting spatial distribution of equipotential surfaces within the device is exceedingly complex.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The capacitance of a connected, or "closed", single-electron device is twice the capacitance of an unconnected, or "open", single-electron device.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] whose energy terms may be obtained as solutions of the Schrödinger equation.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] This expression of "quantum capacitance" may be written as $C_{Q}(N)={e^{2} \over U(N)},$ which differs from the conventional expression described in the introduction where $W_{\text{stored}}=U$ , the stored electrostatic potential energy, $C={Q^{2} \over 2U},$ by a factor of ⁠1/2⁠ with $Q=Ne$ .
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] which is appropriate since $\mathrm {d} q=0$ for systems involving either many electrons or metallic electrodes, but in few-electron systems, $\mathrm {d} q\to \Delta \,Q=e$ .
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The integral generally becomes a summation.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] One may trivially combine the expressions of capacitance $Q=CV$ and electrostatic interaction energy, $U=QV,$ to obtain $C=Q{1 \over V}=Q{Q \over U}={Q^{2} \over U},$ which is similar to the quantum capacitance.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] A more rigorous derivation is reported in the literature.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In particular, to circumvent the mathematical challenges of spatially complex equipotential surfaces within the device, an *average* electrostatic potential experienced by each electron is utilized in the derivation.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Apparent mathematical differences may be understood more fundamentally.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The potential energy, $U(N)$ , of an isolated device (self-capacitance) is twice that stored in a "connected" device in the lower limit $N=1$ .
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In nanoscale devices such as quantum dots, the "capacitor" is often an isolated or partially isolated component within the device.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] The primary differences between nanoscale capacitors and macroscopic (conventional) capacitors are the number of excess electrons (charge carriers, or electrons, that contribute to the device's electronic behavior) and the shape and size of metallic electrodes.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In nanoscale devices, nanowires consisting of metal atoms typically do not exhibit the same conductive properties as their macroscopic, or bulk material, counterparts.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In electronic and semiconductor devices, transient or frequency-dependent current between terminals contains both conduction and displacement components.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Conduction current is related to moving charge carriers (electrons, holes, ions, etc.), while displacement current is caused by a time-varying electric field.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Carrier transport is affected by electric fields and by a number of physical phenomena - such as carrier drift and diffusion, trapping, injection, contact-related effects, impact ionization, etc.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] As a result, device admittance is frequency-dependent, and a simple electrostatic formula for capacitance $C=q/V,$ is not applicable.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] A more general definition of capacitance, encompassing electrostatic formula, is: $C={\frac {\operatorname {Im} (Y(\omega ))}{\omega }},$ where $Y(\omega )$ is the device admittance, and $\omega$ is the angular frequency.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] In general, capacitance is a function of frequency.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] At high frequencies, capacitance approaches a constant value, equal to "geometric" capacitance, determined by the terminals' geometry and dielectric content in the device.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] A paper by Steven Laux presents a review of numerical techniques for capacitance calculation.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Usually, capacitance in semiconductor devices is positive.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] However, in some devices and under certain conditions (temperature, applied voltages, frequency, etc.), capacitance can become negative.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Non-monotonic behavior of the transient current in response to a step-like excitation has been proposed as the mechanism of negative capacitance.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Negative capacitance has been demonstrated and explored in many different types of semiconductor devices.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] A capacitance meter is a piece of electronic test equipment used to measure capacitance, mainly of discrete capacitors.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] For most purposes and in most cases the capacitor must be disconnected from circuit.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Many DVMs (digital volt meters) have a capacitance-measuring function.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] These usually operate by charging and discharging the capacitor under test with a known current and measuring the rate of rise of the resulting voltage; the slower the rate of rise, the larger the capacitance.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] DVMs can usually measure capacitance from nanofarads to a few hundred microfarads, but wider ranges are not unusual.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] It is also possible to measure capacitance by passing a known high-frequency alternating current through the device under test and measuring the resulting voltage across it (does not work for polarised capacitors).
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] More sophisticated instruments use other techniques such as inserting the capacitor-under-test into a bridge circuit.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] By varying the values of the other legs in the bridge (so as to bring the bridge into balance), the value of the unknown capacitor is determined.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] This method of *indirect* use of measuring capacitance ensures greater precision.
[src:electrical-reactance/capacitance] Through the use of Kelvin connections and other careful design techniques, these instruments can usually measure capacitors over a range from picofarads to farads.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] At the time of his death, Steinmetz held over 200 patents.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A genius in both mathematics and electronics, he did work that earned him the nicknames "Forger of Thunderbolts" and "The Wizard of Schenectady".
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was born Karl August Rudolph Steinmetz on April 9, 1865, in Breslau, Province of Silesia, Prussia (now Wrocław, Poland), the son of Caroline (Neubert) and Karl Heinrich Steinmetz.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He was baptized as a Lutheran into the Evangelical Church of Prussia.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz, who stood only 4 ft 0 in (1.22 m) tall as an adult, had dwarfism, hunchback, and hip dysplasia, as did his father and grandfather.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz graduated with honors from St.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Following Gymnasium, Steinmetz studied at the University of Breslau to begin work on his undergraduate degree in 1883.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Nearing completion of his doctorate in 1888, he was forced to flee to Zurich, Switzerland, as the German government was preparing to prosecute him for his socialist activities.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] As socialist meetings and press had been banned in Germany, Steinmetz fled to Zurich in 1889 to escape possible arrest.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Faced with an expiring visa, he emigrated to the United States in 1889 at the age of 24.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He changed his first name to "Charles" to sound more American, and chose the middle name "Proteus", a wise hunchbacked character from the *Odyssey* who knew many secrets, after an epithet bestowed upon him by his college fraternity brothers.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was politically active in the US as a technocratic socialist for over thirty years.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Following the Bolshevik introduction of a technocratic plan to electrify Russia, Steinmetz spoke of Lenin alongside Albert Einstein as the "two greatest minds of our time." He believed in a corporatist industrial government also covering its human welfare function.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A member of the original Technical Alliance, which also included Thorstein Veblen and Leland Olds, Steinmetz had great faith in the ability of machines to eliminate human toil and create abundance for all.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He put it this way: "Some day we [will] make the good things of life for everybody." Steinmetz's techno-utopian optimism was deeply intertwined with his political beliefs, and he was convinced that the spread of electrification would inevitably steer human society toward socialism.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz is known for his contribution in three major fields of alternating current (AC) systems theory: hysteresis, steady-state analysis, and transients.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Shortly after arriving in the United States, Steinmetz went to work for Rudolf Eickemeyer in Yonkers, New York, and published in the field of magnetic hysteresis, earning worldwide professional recognition.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Eickemeyer's firm developed transformers for use in the transmission of electrical power among many other mechanical and electrical devices.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In 1893 Eickemeyer's company, along with all of its patents and designs, was bought by the newly formed General Electric Company, where Steinmetz quickly became known as the engineering wizard in GE's engineering community.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's work revolutionized AC circuit theory and analysis, which had been carried out using complicated, time-consuming calculus-based methods.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In the groundbreaking paper, "Complex Quantities and Their Use in Electrical Engineering", presented at a July 1893 meeting published in the American Institute of Electrical Engineers (AIEE), Steinmetz simplified these complicated methods to "a simple problem of algebra".
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He systematized the use of complex number phasor representation in electrical engineering education texts, whereby the lower-case letter "j" is used to designate the 90-degree rotation operator in AC system analysis.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] His seminal books and many other AIEE papers "taught a whole generation of engineers how to deal with AC phenomena".
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz also greatly advanced the understanding of lightning.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] His systematic experiments resulted in the first laboratory-created "man-made lightning", earning him the nickname "Forger of Thunderbolts".
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] These were conducted in a football-field-sized laboratory at General Electric, using 120 000-volt generators.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Like alternating-current pioneer Nikola Tesla, he also erected a lightning tower to attract natural lightning to study its patterns and effects, which resulted in several theories.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He was granted an honorary degree from Harvard University in 1901 and a doctorate from Union College in 1903.; other awards include the Certificate of Merit of Franklin Institute, 1908; the Elliott Cresson Medal, 1913; and the Cedergren Medal, 1914.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was also an elected member of both the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and the American Philosophical Society.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz wrote 13 books and 60 articles, not exclusively about engineering.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He was a member and adviser to the fraternity Phi Gamma Delta at Union College, whose chapter house was one of the first electrified residences.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] While serving as president of the Schenectady Board of Education, Steinmetz introduced numerous progressive reforms, including extended school hours, school meals, school nurses, special classes for the children of immigrants, and the distribution of free textbooks.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz had dwarfism, standing only 4 ft 0 in (1.22 m) tall as an adult, and was affected by kyphosis like his father and grandfather.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In spite of his love for children and family life, Steinmetz remained unmarried, to prevent his spinal deformity from being passed to any offspring.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] When Joseph LeRoy Hayden, a loyal and hardworking lab assistant, announced that he would marry and look for his own living quarters, Steinmetz made the unusual proposal of opening his large home, complete with research lab, greenhouse, and office to the Haydens and their prospective family.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Hayden favored the idea, but his future wife was wary of the unorthodox arrangement.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] She agreed after Steinmetz's assurance that she could run the house as she saw fit.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] After an uneasy start, the arrangement worked well for all parties, especially after three Hayden children were born.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz legally adopted Joseph Hayden as his son, becoming grandfather to the youngsters, entertaining them with fantastic stories and spectacular scientific demonstrations.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] The unusual, harmonious living arrangement lasted for the rest of Steinmetz's life.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In 1894, Steinmetz founded the *Mohawk Aerial Navigation Company (Ltd.)*, which became the first practical, active gliding club in the world.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He died on October 26, 1923, at the age of 58 and was buried in Vale Cemetery in Schenectady.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz earned wide recognition among the scientific community and numerous awards and honors both during his life and posthumously.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's equation, derived from his experiments, defines the approximate heat energy due to magnetic hysteresis released, per cycle per unit volume of magnetic material.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A Steinmetz solid is the solid body generated by the intersection of two or three cylinders of equal radius at right angles.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's equivalent circuit is still widely used for the design and testing of induction machines.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] One of the highest technical recognitions given by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, the "IEEE Charles Proteus Steinmetz Award", is given for major contributions to standardization within the field of electrical and electronics engineering.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz Memorial Lecture series was begun in his honor in 1925, sponsored by the Schenectady branch of the IEEE.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Through 2017 seventy-three gatherings have taken place, held almost exclusively at Union College, featuring notable figures such as Nobel laureate experimental physicist Robert A.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Millikan, helicopter inventor Igor Sikorsky, nuclear submarine pioneer Admiral Hyman G.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Rickover (1963), Nobel-winning semiconductor inventor William Shockley, and Internet "founding father" Leonard Kleinrock.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's connection to Union is further celebrated with the annual Steinmetz Symposium, a day-long event in which Union undergraduates give presentations on research they have done.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz Hall, which houses the Union College computer center, is named after him.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz Scholarship is awarded annually by the college, underwritten since its inception in 1923 by the General Electric Company.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz Memorial Scholarship was later established at Union by Marjorie Hayden, daughter of Joseph and Corrine Hayden, and is awarded to students majoring in engineering or physics.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A 1914 "Duplex Drive Brougham" Detroit Electric automobile that once belonged to Steinmetz was purchased by Union College in 1971, and restored for use in campus ceremonies.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] The Steinmetz car is permanently displayed in the first-floor corridor between the Wold Center and F.W.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A Chicago public high school, Steinmetz College Prep, is named for him, as well as a Schenectady public school, the Steinmetz Career and Leadership Academy, formerly Steinmetz Middle-School.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A public park in north Schenectady, New York, was named for him in 1931.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In 1983, the US Post Office included Steinmetz in a series of postage stamps commemorating American inventors.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In May 2015, a life-size bronze statue of Charles Steinmetz meeting Thomas Edison by sculptor and caster Dexter Benedict was unveiled on a plaza on the corner of Erie Boulevards and South Ferry Street in Schenectady.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Charles Steinmetz's Mohawk River cabin is preserved and on display in the outdoor collection of historic structures in Greenfield Village, part of the Henry Ford Museum complex in Dearborn, Michigan.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz is featured in John Dos Passos's *U.S.A.* trilogy in one of the biographies.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He also serves as a major character in Starling Lawrence's 2006 book, *The Lightning Keeper*.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz is a major character in the novel *Electric City* by Elizabeth Rosner.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In the 1944 Three Stooges short "Busy Buddies", Moe Howard references Steinmetz.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was portrayed in 1959 by the actor Rod Steiger in the CBS television anthology series, *The Joseph Cotten Show*.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] The episode focused on his socialist activities in Germany.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A famous anecdote about Steinmetz concerns a troubleshooting consultation at Henry Ford's River Rouge Plant.
[src:electrical-reactance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A humorous aspect of the story is the "itemized bill" he submitted for the work performed.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] In electrical circuits, **reactance** is the opposition presented to alternating current by inductance and capacitance.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Greater reactance gives smaller current for the same applied voltage.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Reactance is used to compute amplitude and phase changes of sinusoidal alternating current going through a circuit element.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Like resistance, reactance is measured in ohms, with positive values indicating **inductive** reactance and negative indicating **capacitive** reactance.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] An ideal resistor has zero reactance, whereas ideal reactors have no shunt conductance and no series resistance.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] As frequency increases, inductive reactance increases and capacitive reactance decreases.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Reactance is similar to resistance in that larger reactance leads to smaller currents for the same applied voltage.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Furthermore, a circuit made entirely of elements that have only reactance (and no resistance) can be treated the same way as a circuit made entirely of resistances.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] These same techniques can also be used to combine elements with reactance with elements with resistance, but complex numbers are typically needed.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] This is treated below in the section on impedance.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] There are several important differences between reactance and resistance, though.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] First, reactance changes the phase so that the current through the element is shifted by a quarter of a cycle relative to the phase of the voltage applied across the element.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Second, power is not dissipated in a purely reactive element but is stored instead.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Third, reactances can be negative so that they can 'cancel' each other out.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Finally, the main circuit elements that have reactance (capacitors and inductors) have a frequency dependent reactance, unlike resistors which have the same resistance for all frequencies, at least in the ideal case.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] The term *reactance* was first suggested by French engineer Édouard Hospitalier in *L'Industrie Electrique* on 10 May 1893.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] It was officially adopted by the American Institute of Electrical Engineers in May 1894.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] A capacitor consists of two conductors separated by an insulator, also known as a dielectric.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] There are two choices in the literature for defining reactance for a capacitor.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] In this case however one needs to remember to add a negative sign for the impedance of a capacitor, i.e. ⁠ $Z_{c}=-jX_{c}$ ⁠.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] At ⁠ $f=0$ ⁠, the magnitude of the capacitor's reactance is infinite, behaving like an open circuit (preventing any current from flowing through the dielectric).
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] As frequency increases, the magnitude of reactance decreases, allowing more current to flow.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] As f approaches ⁠ $\infty$ ⁠, the capacitor's reactance approaches ⁠ 0 ⁠, behaving like a short circuit.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] The application of a DC voltage across a capacitor causes positive charge to accumulate on one side and negative charge to accumulate on the other side; the electric field due to the accumulated charge is the source of the opposition to the current.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] When the potential associated with the charge exactly balances the applied voltage, the current goes to zero.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Driven by an AC supply (ideal AC current source), a capacitor will only accumulate a limited amount of charge before the potential difference changes polarity and the charge is returned to the source.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] The higher the frequency, the less charge will accumulate and the smaller the opposition to the current.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Inductive reactance is a property exhibited by an inductor, and inductive reactance exists based on the fact that an electric current produces a magnetic field around it.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] In the context of an AC circuit (although this concept applies any time current is changing), this magnetic field is constantly changing as a result of current that oscillates back and forth.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] It is this change in magnetic field that induces another electric current to flow in the same wire – called counter-electromotive force (counter-EMF) – in a direction such as to oppose the flow of the current originally responsible for producing the magnetic field (known as Lenz's law).
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Hence, **inductive reactance** is an opposition to the change of current through an element.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] For an ideal inductor in an AC circuit, the inhibitive effect on change in current flow results in a delay, or a phase shift, of the alternating current with respect to alternating voltage.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Specifically, an ideal inductor (with no resistance) will cause the current to lag the voltage by a quarter cycle, or 90°.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] In electric power systems, inductive reactance (and capacitive reactance, however inductive reactance is more common) can limit the power capacity of an AC transmission line, because power is not completely transferred when voltage and current are out-of-phase (detailed above).
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] That is, current will flow for an out-of-phase system, however real power at certain times will not be transferred, because there will be points during which instantaneous current is positive while instantaneous voltage is negative, or vice versa, implying negative power transfer.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Hence, real work is not performed when power transfer is "negative".
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] However, current still flows even when a system is out-of-phase, which causes transmission lines to heat up due to current flow.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Power providers utilize capacitors to shift the phase and minimize the losses, based on usage patterns.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Any conductor of finite dimensions has inductance; the inductance is made larger by the multiple turns in an electromagnetic coil.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] The counter-emf is the source of the opposition to current flow.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] A constant direct current has a zero rate-of-change, and sees an inductor as a short-circuit (it is typically made from a material with a low resistivity).
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] An alternating current has a time-averaged rate-of-change that is proportional to frequency, this causes the increase in inductive reactance with frequency.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] When both a capacitor and an inductor are placed in series in a circuit, their contributions to the total circuit impedance are opposite.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Note however that if $X_{L}$ and $X_{C}$ are assumed both positive by definition, then the intermediary formula changes to a difference: ${X=X_{L}-X_{C}=\omega L-{\frac {1}{\omega C}}},$ but the ultimate value is the same.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] The phase of the voltage across a purely reactive device (i.e. with zero parasitic resistance) *lags* the current by ${\tfrac {\pi }{2}}$ radians for a capacitive reactance and *leads* the current by ${\tfrac {\pi }{2}}$ radians for an inductive reactance.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] Without knowledge of both the resistance and reactance the relationship between voltage and current cannot be determined.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] For a reactive component the sinusoidal voltage across the component is in quadrature (a ${\tfrac {\pi }{2}}$ phase difference) with the sinusoidal current through the component.
[src:electrical-reactance/electrical-reactance] The component alternately absorbs energy from the circuit and then returns energy to the circuit, thus a pure reactance does not dissipate power.
